Claims CLAIMS WHAT IS CLAIMED IS: 1. A non-transitory computer-readable medium comprising stored instructions executable by at least one processor for determining risk level within an enterprise computing environment, the instructions when executed causing the at least one processor to: determine that a policy is to be executed; retrieve rules, resource identifiers, and data provider identifiers associated with the policy; asynchronously retrieve resources from data providers that are called for by the rules; execute each of the rules as their corresponding resources are retrieved; identify a group of rules that have failed; calculate a risk score for each rule of the group; generate an alert for each rule of the group; and output a report including each alert, each of the alerts being prioritized in the report based on the risk score of their corresponding rule. 2. The non-transitory computer-readable medium of claim 1, wherein the instructions to determine that the policy is to be executed when executed cause the one or more processors to: access a last time the policy was executed; generate a run time for the policy by adding a scanning interval to the last time the policy was executed; determine whether the run time is less than or equal to a current time; and responsive to determining that the run time is less than or equal to the current time, determine that the policy is to be executed. 3. The non-transitory computer-readable medium of claim 1, wherein at least two of the rules call for retrieval of a same resource, and wherein the same resource is retrieved only once. 4. The non-transitory computer-readable medium of claim 3, wherein a first of the at least two rules calls for retrieval of the same resource from a first data provider, wherein a second of the at least two rules calls for retrieval of the same resource from a second data provider, wherein the same resource is retrieved from the first data 

 provider, and wherein the second rule is executed using the same resource retrieved from the first data provider. 5. The non-transitory computer-readable medium of claim 3, wherein the instructions to execute each of the rules as their corresponding resources are retrieved cause the one or more processors to: determine, for each given rule, whether all resources called for by the given rule have been retrieved; and responsive to determining that all resources called for by the given rule have been retrieved, execute the given rule. 6. The non-transitory computer-readable medium of claim 1, wherein the instructions to calculate the risk score for each rule of the group when executed cause the one or more processors to weight the risk score based on an amount of time that has passed since each rule was initially determined to have failed. 7. The non-transitory computer-readable medium of claim 1, wherein the one or more processors are further caused, when executing the instructions, to: calculate a policy risk score for each policy having a rule that has failed, wherein the policy risk score is an accumulation of risk scores for each rule in the policy; generate an alert for each policy having a rule that has failed; and include the alert for each policy having a rule that has failed in the report. 8. A method for determining risk level within an enterprise computing environment, the method comprising: determining that a policy is to be executed; retrieving rules, resource identifiers, and data provider identifiers associated with the policy; asynchronously retrieving resources from data providers that are called for by the rules; executing each of the rules as their corresponding resources are retrieved; identifying a group of rules that have failed; calculating a risk score for each rule of the group; generating an alert for each rule of the group; and outputting a report including each alert, each of the alerts being prioritized in the report based on the risk score of their corresponding rule. 9. The method of claim 8, wherein determining that the policy is to be executed comprises: accessing a last time the policy was executed; generating a run time for the policy by adding a scanning interval to the last time the policy was executed; determining whether the run time is less than or equal to a current time; and responsive to determining that the run time is less than or equal to the current time, determining that the policy is to be executed. 10. The method of claim 8, wherein at least two of the rules call for retrieval of a same resource, and wherein the same resource is retrieved only once. 11. The method of claim 10, wherein a first of the at least two rules calls for retrieval of the same resource from a first data provider, wherein a second of the at least two rules calls for retrieval of the same resource from a second data provider, wherein the same resource is retrieved from the first data provider, and wherein the second rule is executed using the same resource retrieved from the first data provider. 12. The method of claim 10, wherein executing each of the rules as their corresponding resources are retrieved comprises: determining, for each given rule, whether all resources called for by the given rule have been retrieved; and responsive to determining that all resources called for by the given rule have been retrieved, executing the given rule. 13. The method of claim 8, wherein calculating the risk score for each rule of the group comprises weighting the risk score based on an amount of time that has passed since each rule was initially determined to have failed. 14. The method of claim 8, further comprising: calculating a policy risk score for each policy having a rule that has failed, wherein the policy risk score is an accumulation of risk scores for each rule in the policy; generating an alert for each policy having a rule that has failed; and including the alert for each policy having a rule that has fail